istorians, practitioners and policy makers to consider the past, present and future of hospital infection control. Combining historical case-studies with practitioner experiences, this volume offers a new understanding of the emergence of theories of germ transmission and containment and how these theories played out in real-world environments, networks and professional organisations.Exploring the historical context in which technologies like gloves were developed and popularised, as well as how relationships between communities and hospitals, doctors and nurses, and the emerging role of hospital bacteriologists have shaped infection control practices, the collection emphasises the diverse contexts in which ideas about germs, infection and safety circulated. The volume also addresses the historical neglect of the critical role of nurses in the development and success of infection control measures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHospital buildingsxSanitationxHistory. 0aHospital buildingsxSanitation. 0aHospitalsxAdministrationxHistory. 0aHospitalsxAdministration. 0aNosocomial infectionsxHistory. 0aNosocomial infectionsxPreventionxHistory. 0aNosocomial infectionsxPrevention. 0aNosocomial infections. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aanti-microbial resistance.  aantisepsis/asepsis.  abacteriology.  acommunity.  adoctors.  ahealthcare.  ahistory.  ahospital.  ainfection.  anurses.1 aAlberti, Fay Bound, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBound Alberti, Fay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCondrau, Flurin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCresswell, Rosemary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDupree, Marguerite, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov